Egyptâ€™s benchmark  EGX 30 Index (EGX30) 
advanced 1.7 percent, the most since July 17, to 5,007.5 at the
1:30 p.m. close in Cairo. The measure has declined 0.3 percent
this week.  The following shares rose or fell. Symbols are in
parentheses.  Alexandria Portland Cement Co. (ALEX EY) jumped 4.9
percent, the most in more than four months, to 13.74 Egyptian
pounds. The producer of the building material said six-month
profit rose 25 percent to 357.9 million pounds ($60 million)
compared with a year earlier.  Citadel Capital Holding SAE (CCAP EY) gained for the first
time in three days, climbing 2.8 percent to 4.8 pounds.
Shareholders of the Cairo-based private equity firm approved a
1.05 billion pound rights offer. The company will use the funds
to finance expansion and current investments.  Lecico  Egypt  (LCSW EY) rose 2.1 percent, the biggest gain
in more than three weeks, to 9.81 pounds. The tiles and sanitary
ware manufacturer said production resumed today at its factories
in Alexandria after a nine-day labor strike ended.  National Societe Generale Bank (NSGB EY) advanced 1.3
percent, the most since July 13, to 31.41 pounds. The second-
biggest publicly traded bank by assets in Egypt said its second-
quarter profit increased 14 percent to 369.2 million pounds from
a year earlier.  To contact the reporter on this story:
